When you override equals() without hashCode(), you violate the Java contract that states: if two objects are equal according to equals(), they must have the same hashCode(). This creates catastrophic behavior in hash-based collections.

The production impact is severe. Consider a HashMap storing user objects as keys:

```java
class User {
    String id;
    String email;

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (!(o instanceof User)) return false;
        return this.id.equals(((User) o).id);
    }
    // Missing hashCode()!
}

Map<User, String> cache = new HashMap<>();
User user1 = new User("1", "alice@example.com");
cache.put(user1, "active");

User user2 = new User("1", "alice@example.com");
System.out.println(cache.get(user2)); // Returns null!
```

Each User gets a random hashCode() from Object class. user1 and user2 are equals(), but different hashCodes send them to different buckets. The lookup fails silently. This bug is notorious because it passes unit tests locally but manifests as mysterious NPEs in distributed caches (Redis serialization), session management, and deduplication logic.

HashMap in Java 8+ uses bucket-based hashing with dynamic switching to Red-Black trees for collision resolution. The key structural improvement is the TREEIFY_THRESHOLD of 8.

**Internal structure:**
- Array of buckets (Node<K,V>[])
- Each bucket is a linked list that converts to a tree at threshold
- Uses xxHash64-like function for key distribution

**How it works:**

```java
// Internal structure (simplified)
static class Node<K,V> {
    int hash;
    K key;
    V value;
    Node<K,V> next;
}

class HashMap<K,V> {
    Node<K,V>[] table;

    public V put(K key, V value) {
        int hash = hash(key);
        int index = (table.length - 1) & hash; // Fast modulo

        Node<K,V> node = table[index];
        while (node != null) {
            if (node.hash == hash && node.key.equals(key)) {
                V old = node.value;
                node.value = value;
                return old;
            }
            node = node.next;
        }
        // Insert new node
        addNode(hash, key, value, index);
        return null;
    }
}
```

**Resizing strategy:**
- Threshold = capacity × loadFactor (default 0.75)
- When size > threshold, double the capacity and rehash all entries
- Capacity is always power of 2 for efficient bitwise operations

HashMap converts a bucket from linked list to Red-Black Tree when TWO conditions are met:

1. The bucket size (chain length) reaches TREEIFY_THRESHOLD = 8
2. The HashMap capacity is >= MIN_TREEIFY_CAPACITY = 64

The second condition is crucial: small HashMaps resize instead of tree-ifying.

**The exact code logic:**

```java
// From HashMap.putVal()
if (e != null) { // hash collision
    V oldValue = e.value;
    if (!onlyIfAbsent || oldValue == null)
        e.value = value;
    afterNodeAccess(e);
    return oldValue;
}
addNode(hash, key, value, index);

// In addNode()
++size;
if (size - (table.length - (table.length >> 2)) > 0) {
    resize(); // Double capacity instead of tree-ifying
}

// But if we're treeifying:
if (binCount >= TREEIFY_THRESHOLD - 1) {
    treeifyBin(table, hash);
}

private void treeifyBin(Node<K,V>[] tab, int hash) {
    int n;
    if (tab == null || (n = tab.length) < MIN_TREEIFY_CAPACITY)
        resize(); // Still too small, resize instead
    else {
        // Convert to TreeNode and rebalance as Red-Black tree
        TreeNode<K,V> hd = null, tl = null;
        for (Node<K,V> e = tab[index]; e != null; e = e.next) {
            TreeNode<K,V> p = new TreeNode<K,V>(e.hash, e.key, e.value, null);
            if (tl == null)
                hd = p;
            else {
                p.prev = tl;
                tl.next = p;
            }
            tl = p;
        }
        if ((tab[index] = hd) != null)
            hd.treeify(null);
    }
}
```

Why both conditions? Tree-ifying has overhead. Small maps benefit from resizing instead. Once a bucket becomes a tree, lookups drop from O(n) to O(log n) under collisions.

String immutability in Java provides critical security and performance guarantees. It's not just design—it's fundamental.

**Security reasons:**

```java
String username = "admin";
String password = "secret123";

// If Strings were mutable:
String[] userData = {username, password};
hackersCode.modifyString(userData[1]); // password changed to "hacked"!

// Real security issue: Spring Security authentication
String inputPassword = "user123";
authenticate(inputPassword);
// Attacker modifies inputPassword after authentication check
// -> Attacker gains access with different password

// String pool security
String s1 = "admin"; // Goes to String pool
String s2 = new String("admin"); // Separate object
if (s1 == s2) verify(); // false - but immutability prevents swapping pool reference
```

**Performance reasons:**

```java
// Without immutability: expensive copying
String original = "largeStringValue";
String copy1 = original; // Would need deep copy
String copy2 = original; // Would need deep copy
// Memory waste!

// With immutability: safe sharing
String url = "https://example.com/api";
Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> sendRequest(url)); // No synchronization needed
Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> sendRequest(url));
t1.start(); t2.start();

// String interning optimization
String a = "database";
String b = "database";
System.out.println(a == b); // true - same reference due to immutability
// Saves memory in long-running applications
```

**HashCode caching:**
```java
// HashMap lookups cache the hashCode
class CachedHashString {
    private final String value;
    private final int cachedHash;

    public CachedHashString(String value) {
        this.value = value;
        this.cachedHash = value.hashCode();
    }
    // hashCode() always returns same cached value - no recalculation!
}
```

Without immutability, cached hashCodes would be invalid if the String changed.

Comparable provides natural ordering (one way), while Comparator enables multiple sort strategies. Comparable requires implementing the interface; Comparator is a separate definition.

**Key difference:**

```java
// Comparable: ONE natural ordering
class Employee implements Comparable<Employee> {
    int id;
    String name;
    double salary;

    @Override
    public int compareTo(Employee other) {
        return this.id - other.id; // Natural order by ID
    }
}

List<Employee> employees = List.of(emp1, emp2, emp3);
Collections.sort(employees); // Uses compareTo()

// Comparator: Multiple custom orderings
Comparator<Employee> byName = (e1, e2) -> e1.name.compareTo(e2.name);
Comparator<Employee> bySalary = (e1, e2) -> Double.compare(e1.salary, e2.salary);
Comparator<Employee> byNameThenSalary = byName.thenComparing(bySalary);

employees.stream()
    .sorted(byNameThenSalary)
    .forEach(System.out::println);

// Chain multiple sorts
Comparator<Employee> complex = Comparator
    .comparing(Employee::getDepartment)
    .thenComparing(Employee::getSalary).reversed()
    .thenComparing(Employee::getName);
```

**Real scenario - sorting by multiple criteria:**

```java
// Payroll system needs three sort orders
List<Employee> emps = getEmployees();

// 1. By salary descending
emps.sort(Comparator.comparingDouble(Employee::getSalary).reversed());

// 2. By hire date ascending
emps.sort(Comparator.comparing(Employee::getHireDate));

// 3. By department, then salary, then alphabetically
emps.sort(Comparator
    .comparing(Employee::getDepartment)
    .thenComparingDouble(Employee::getSalary)
    .thenComparing(Employee::getName));

// Without Comparator: Would need separate sorting logic
// With Comparable: Only one natural order possible
```

Comparable locks you into one order; Comparator gives unlimited flexibility.

map() transforms 1-to-1 (each element to one result), while flatMap() transforms 1-to-many and flattens the result. Critical for nested structures.

**Conceptual difference:**

```java
// map(): element -> new element
List<Integer> numbers = List.of(1, 2, 3);
List<Integer> squared = numbers.stream()
    .map(n -> n * n)
    .collect(toList()); // [1, 4, 9]

// flatMap(): element -> stream of elements -> flattened
List<String> words = List.of("hello", "world");
List<String> characters = words.stream()
    .flatMap(word -> Stream.of(word.split("")))
    .collect(toList()); // [h, e, l, l, o, w, o, r, l, d]

// Real difference:
List<List<Integer>> nested = List.of(
    List.of(1, 2),
    List.of(3, 4)
);

// map keeps nesting
List<List<Integer>> withMap = nested.stream()
    .map(list -> list.stream().map(x -> x * 2).collect(toList()))
    .collect(toList()); // [[2, 4], [6, 8]]

// flatMap flattens
List<Integer> withFlatMap = nested.stream()
    .flatMap(list -> list.stream().map(x -> x * 2))
    .collect(toList()); // [2, 4, 6, 8]
```

**Real project example - Order processing:**

```java
// Order contains multiple LineItems, each with multiple StockUnits
class Order {
    List<LineItem> items;
}
class LineItem {
    List<StockUnit> units;
    String productId;
}

// Get all stock units across all orders
List<StockUnit> allUnits = orders.stream()
    .flatMap(order -> order.getItems().stream())
    .flatMap(item -> item.getUnits().stream())
    .filter(unit -> unit.isAvailable())
    .collect(toList());

// Without flatMap: nested loops
List<StockUnit> manual = new ArrayList<>();
for (Order order : orders) {
    for (LineItem item : order.getItems()) {
        for (StockUnit unit : item.getUnits()) {
            if (unit.isAvailable()) {
                manual.add(unit);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

flatMap solves the flattening problem; map can't.

findFirst() returns first element in encounter order and is deterministic; findAny() returns any element and is non-deterministic. In parallel streams, findAny() is significantly faster.

**Encounter order behavior:**

```java
List<Integer> numbers = List.of(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);

// Sequential: both return 1 (first in order)
numbers.stream()
    .filter(n -> n > 0)
    .findFirst(); // Always 1

numbers.stream()
    .filter(n -> n > 0)
    .findAny(); // Also 1 in sequential

// Parallel: major difference
numbers.parallelStream()
    .filter(n -> n > 0)
    .findFirst(); // Returns 1, but requires coordination across threads

numbers.parallelStream()
    .filter(n -> n > 0)
    .findAny(); // May return any of [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] without coordination
```

**Performance impact on large data:**

```java
List<Integer> largeList = new ArrayList<>();
for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++) largeList.add(i);

// findFirst() is SLOW in parallel
long start = System.nanoTime();
Integer first = largeList.parallelStream()
    .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)
    .findFirst() // Barrier: waits for first thread to find element
    .orElse(null);
long durationFirst = System.nanoTime() - start;

// findAny() is FAST in parallel
start = System.nanoTime();
Integer any = largeList.parallelStream()
    .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)
    .findAny() // No barrier: returns whenever any thread finds it
    .orElse(null);
long durationAny = System.nanoTime() - start;
// durationAny is typically 10x faster

System.out.println("findFirst: " + durationFirst);
System.out.println("findAny: " + durationAny);
```

**When to use which:**
- findFirst(): Need guaranteed encounter order
- findAny(): Performance matters, order doesn't (searching exists, etc.)

Streams have overhead: object creation, function calls, and GC pressure. For-loops are faster for small datasets and CPU-bound work.

**Performance comparison:**

```java
List<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();
for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++) {
    numbers.add(i);
}

// Streams: slower
long start = System.nanoTime();
List<Integer> streamResult = numbers.stream()
    .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)
    .map(n -> n * 2)
    .filter(n -> n < 1_000_000)
    .collect(toList());
long streamTime = System.nanoTime() - start;

// For-loop: faster
start = System.nanoTime();
List<Integer> loopResult = new ArrayList<>();
for (Integer n : numbers) {
    if (n % 2 == 0) {
        int doubled = n * 2;
        if (doubled < 1_000_000) {
            loopResult.add(doubled);
        }
    }
}
long loopTime = System.nanoTime() - start;
// loopTime is typically 30-50% faster

System.out.println("Stream: " + streamTime / 1_000_000 + "ms");
System.out.println("Loop: " + loopTime / 1_000_000 + "ms");
```

**When streams perform worse:**
1. Very large intermediate objects being created
2. Tight CPU-bound loops (where throughput matters)
3. Processing millions of objects with multiple filters
4. Short-lived collections with few elements
5. GC-sensitive applications

**When streams excel:**
- Readability matters more than micro-seconds
- Working with streams of data (I/O, network)
- Complex data transformations with multiple operations
- Parallel processing (ForkJoinPool efficiency)

**Real benchmark:**
```java
// For 100 elements: streams ~same
// For 1M elements: for-loops 20-40% faster
// For I/O operations: streams irrelevant (I/O dominates)
```

The myth: "Streams are always better." Reality: They're better for readability and maintainability, not always speed.

groupingBy() groups elements by a classifier function, optionally applying a downstream collector to aggregate values within each group.

**Basic structure:**

```java
class Employee {
    String department;
    String name;
    double salary;
}

List<Employee> employees = getEmployees();

// Simple grouping by department
Map<String, List<Employee>> byDept = employees.stream()
    .collect(groupingBy(Employee::getDepartment));
// {IT: [emp1, emp2], HR: [emp3], Finance: [emp4, emp5]}

// groupingBy with downstream collector (count)
Map<String, Long> deptCounts = employees.stream()
    .collect(groupingBy(
        Employee::getDepartment,
        counting()
    ));
// {IT: 2, HR: 1, Finance: 2}

// Multiple downstream collectors
Map<String, DoubleSummaryStatistics> salaryStats = employees.stream()
    .collect(groupingBy(
        Employee::getDepartment,
        summarizingDouble(Employee::getSalary)
    ));
// {IT: DoubleSummaryStatistics{count=2, sum=150000, ...}, ...}

// Nested grouping (multiple levels)
Map<String, Map<String, List<Employee>>> byDeptAndGender = employees.stream()
    .collect(groupingBy(
        Employee::getDepartment,
        groupingBy(Employee::getGender)
    ));
// {IT: {M: [emp1], F: [emp2]}, HR: {M: [emp3]}}

// Complex downstream - max salary per department
Map<String, Optional<Employee>> topEarner = employees.stream()
    .collect(groupingBy(
        Employee::getDepartment,
        maxBy(comparingDouble(Employee::getSalary))
    ));
```

**Real production example:**

```java
// E-commerce: Group orders by customer, then aggregate stats
Map<String, OrderStats> customerMetrics = orders.stream()
    .collect(groupingBy(
        Order::getCustomerId,
        Collector.of(
            OrderStats::new,
            (stats, order) -> {
                stats.totalOrders++;
                stats.totalSpent += order.getAmount();
                stats.avgOrderValue = stats.totalSpent / stats.totalOrders;
            },
            (stats1, stats2) -> {
                stats1.totalOrders += stats2.totalOrders;
                stats1.totalSpent += stats2.totalSpent;
                return stats1;
            }
        )
    ));
```

groupingBy is the cornerstone of complex aggregations without writing explicit loops.

Optional as a field invites bugs: null references, serialization issues, and confuses intent. Use Optional only for return values and method parameters.

**Why NOT as a field:**

```java
// BAD: Optional as field
class User {
    String id;
    Optional<String> middleName; // WRONG!

    public User(String id, String middleName) {
        this.id = id;
        this.middleName = Optional.ofNullable(middleName);
    }

    public String getMiddleName() {
        return middleName.orElse(""); // Still can access null!
    }
}

// Problem 1: Adds null reference to avoid... null references
User user = new User("1", null);
// user.middleName is NOT null, it's Optional.empty()
// But what if developer forgets Optional?
if (user.middleName == null) { // Never true, subtle bug
    user.middleName = Optional.empty();
}

// Problem 2: Serialization nightmare
ObjectOutputStream oos = new ObjectOutputStream(file);
oos.writeObject(user); // Optional not Serializable!

// Problem 3: Entity bloat
@Entity
class Employee {
    Optional<String> department; // JPA won't map properly
    Optional<Double> bonus; // Type mismatch in database
}
```

**Correct usage patterns:**

```java
// GOOD: Optional in return types
class UserService {
    public Optional<User> findUserById(String id) {
        // Signals "user might not exist"
        return db.query(id).isEmpty() ? 
            Optional.empty() : 
            Optional.of(result);
    }

    // Client clearly handles absence
    userService.findUserById("1")
        .ifPresent(user -> processUser(user));
}

// GOOD: Optional in method parameters
void processOrder(Optional<Discount> discount) {
    double amount = discount
        .map(Discount::getAmount)
        .orElse(0.0);
}

// GOOD: For entity fields - use nullable primitive
@Entity
class Employee {
    String middleName; // null is fine, simpler
    Double bonus; // nullable Double, standard

    public Optional<String> getMiddleName() {
        // Optional at API boundary, not in data model
        return Optional.ofNullable(middleName);
    }
}
```

Optional was designed for method chaining and fluent APIs, not as a null wrapper.

@Component, @Service, and @Repository are functionally identical (all are @Component), but semantically different. They signal intent and enable specialized handling.

**Technical difference:**

```java
// All three create beans and enable @Autowired injection
// But they signal different purposes to developers

@Component // Generic component, no semantic meaning
class GenericProcessor {
    public void process() {}
}

@Service // Business logic/use cases
class PaymentService {
    @Autowired
    private PaymentRepository repository;

    public void processPayment(Payment p) {
        // High-level business logic
        validate(p);
        repository.save(p);
        notifyCustomer(p);
    }
}

@Repository // Data access layer
class PaymentRepository {
    @Autowired
    private JdbcTemplate jdbc;

    public void save(Payment p) {
        // Low-level DB operations
        jdbc.update("INSERT INTO payments ...", p.getAmount());
    }
}
```

**Real difference - Exception translation:**

```java
// ONLY @Repository translates database exceptions!
@Repository
class UserRepository {
    @Autowired
    private JdbcTemplate jdbc;

    public User findById(String id) {
        try {
            return jdbc.query(...);
        } catch (DataAccessException e) {
            // Spring automatically translates DB exceptions
            // SQLException -> DataAccessException
            // -> Can catch generic DataAccessException
        }
    }
}

// @Service won't translate
@Service
class PaymentService {
    public void pay() {
        // Raw database exceptions bubble up unhandled
        // Must manually catch and handle
    }
}

// AOP and transaction handling
@Service
class OrderService {
    @Transactional // Works best with @Service
    public void createOrder(Order o) {
        // Transaction management automatic
    }
}
```

**In Spring Boot context:**

```java
// For documentation and future developers
@Component // "I'm a generic helper"
class StringUtil {
    public static String format(String s) { return s; }
}

@Service // "I contain business logic"
class OrderProcessingService {
    public Order processOrder(Order o) { }
}

@Repository // "I handle data access"
class OrderJpaRepository extends JpaRepository<Order, Long> { }
```

Same functionality, different semantics. Using correct annotations makes code self-documenting.

Spring Bean lifecycle has 12+ stages from instantiation to destruction. Understanding when each hook fires is crucial for initialization logic.

**Complete lifecycle:**

```java
@Component
class DatabaseConnection implements InitializingBean, DisposableBean {

    // Stage 1: Instantiation (constructor)
    public DatabaseConnection() {
        System.out.println("1. Constructor called");
    }

    // Stage 2: Property injection
    @Autowired
    private ConfigService config;

    // Stage 3: BeanNameAware.setBeanName()
    @Override
    public void setBeanName(String name) {
        System.out.println("3. Bean name: " + name);
    }

    // Stage 4: BeanClassLoaderAware
    // Stage 5: BeanFactoryAware

    // Stage 6: @PostConstruct hook
    @PostConstruct
    public void init() {
        System.out.println("6. @PostConstruct - Initialize DB connection pool");
        // Run after all properties set, before bean is returned
    }

    // Stage 7: InitializingBean.afterPropertiesSet()
    @Override
    public void afterPropertiesSet() throws Exception {
        System.out.println("7. afterPropertiesSet()");
        // Alternative to @PostConstruct
    }

    // Stage 8: Custom init-method (if specified in config)
    public void customInit() {
        System.out.println("8. Custom init-method");
    }

    // ======== BEAN IS NOW READY FOR USE ========

    // Stage 9-11: Bean is used by application
    public void query(String sql) {
        System.out.println("9-11. Executing: " + sql);
    }

    // Stage 12: @PreDestroy hook
    @PreDestroy
    public void cleanup() {
        System.out.println("12. @PreDestroy - Close connections");
    }

    // Stage 13: DisposableBean.destroy()
    @Override
    public void destroy() {
        System.out.println("13. destroy()");
    }
}

// The sequence fire in order: 1->2->3->6->7->8->ready->12->13
```

**Real production example:**

```java
@Service
public class CacheManager {
    private RedisTemplate<String, Object> redis;

    @PostConstruct // Fire after dependencies injected
    public void initialize() {
        // Connect to Redis
        // Pre-warm cache with static data
        // Validate connectivity
        redis.opsForValue().set("startup", LocalDateTime.now());
    }

    @PreDestroy // Fire before bean destroyed
    public void shutdown() {
        // Flush pending writes to disk
        // Close Redis connections
        // Log shutdown event
        redis.getConnectionFactory().getConnection().close();
    }
}

// Usage
@SpringBootApplication
public class App {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ApplicationContext ctx = SpringApplication.run(App.class);
        CacheManager cache = ctx.getBean(CacheManager.class);
        // @PostConstruct already fired automatically

        // On shutdown:
        ctx.close(); // Triggers @PreDestroy on all beans
    }
}
```

Missing initialization often causes NullPointerException at runtime. Missing cleanup causes resource leaks.

REQUIRED (default) uses existing transaction or creates new one; REQUIRES_NEW always creates new transaction, suspending the current one. Critical for independent operations.

**Behavioral difference:**

```java
@Service
public class WalletService {
    @Autowired
    private WalletRepository walletRepo;

    @Autowired
    private AuditService auditService;

    // REQUIRED: uses parent transaction (default)
    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRED)
    public void transfer(String from, String to, double amount) {
        Wallet w1 = walletRepo.findById(from);
        Wallet w2 = walletRepo.findById(to);

        w1.debit(amount);
        w2.credit(amount);

        walletRepo.save(w1);
        walletRepo.save(w2);

        // If auditLog() throws exception: ENTIRE transfer rolls back!
        auditService.logTransfer(from, to, amount);
    }

    // REQUIRES_NEW: independent transaction
    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void logTransfer(String from, String to, double amount) {
        // NEW transaction started, parent SUSPENDED
        AuditLog log = new AuditLog(from, to, amount);
        auditRepo.save(log);

        // If this FAILS: transfer is NOT rolled back
        // If this SUCCEEDS: log is saved even if transfer fails later
    }
}

// Usage scenario:
// Caller invokes transfer()
// -> Starts transaction T1
//    -> Calls logTransfer()
//       -> Suspends T1
//       -> Starts new transaction T2
//       -> Logs audit entry
//       -> T2 commits (log saved permanently)
//    -> Resumes T1
//    -> If any exception: T1 rolls back (money reverted)
//       -> But audit log T2 already committed
```

**Real production example:**

```java
@Service
public class PaymentProcessor {

    @Transactional // REQUIRED by default
    public void processPayment(Payment payment) {
        payment.setStatus("PROCESSING");
        paymentRepository.save(payment);

        // Charge credit card
        ChargeResult result = paymentGateway.charge(payment.getAmount());

        if (!result.isSuccess()) {
            throw new PaymentFailedException(result.getError());
            // Transaction rolls back: payment status reverted
        }

        payment.setStatus("COMPLETED");
        paymentRepository.save(payment);

        // Send confirmation email - REQUIRES_NEW
        try {
            emailService.sendConfirmation(payment); // Independent
        } catch (Exception e) {
            // Email failure doesn't rollback payment!
            log.error("Email failed, but payment was processed");
        }
    }
}

@Service
public class EmailService {

    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void sendConfirmation(Payment p) {
        // NEW transaction: parent SUSPENDED
        EmailLog log = new EmailLog(p.getId(), "SENT");
        emailRepository.save(log);

        // Send via SMTP (slow, might timeout)
        smtpGateway.send(p.getCustomer().getEmail(), "Confirmation");
        // If fails: log transaction still committed
    }
}
```

**When to use which:**
- REQUIRED: Normal operations (default)
- REQUIRES_NEW: Audit logging, notifications, retries that must succeed independently

Design global exception handling using @ControllerAdvice and @ExceptionHandler to catch exceptions centrally, avoiding try-catch boilerplate in every controller.

**Implementation pattern:**

```java
@RestControllerAdvice // Applies to all @RestController
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {

    // Handle business logic exceptions
    @ExceptionHandler(PaymentException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponse> handlePaymentException(
        PaymentException ex, 
        HttpServletRequest request) {

        ErrorResponse error = ErrorResponse.builder()
            .timestamp(LocalDateTime.now())
            .status(HttpStatus.PAYMENT_REQUIRED.value())
            .message("Payment processing failed")
            .details(ex.getMessage())
            .path(request.getRequestURI())
            .build();

        return new ResponseEntity<>(error, HttpStatus.PAYMENT_REQUIRED);
    }

    // Handle validation errors
    @ExceptionHandler(MethodArgumentNotValidException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponse> handleValidation(
        MethodArgumentNotValidException ex) {

        Map<String, String> errors = new HashMap<>();
        ex.getBindingResult().getFieldErrors().forEach(error ->
            errors.put(error.getField(), error.getDefaultMessage())
        );

        ErrorResponse response = ErrorResponse.builder()
            .timestamp(LocalDateTime.now())
            .status(HttpStatus.BAD_REQUEST.value())
            .message("Validation failed")
            .errors(errors)
            .build();

        return new ResponseEntity<>(response, HttpStatus.BAD_REQUEST);
    }

    // Handle all uncaught exceptions
    @ExceptionHandler(Exception.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponse> handleGlobalException(
        Exception ex, 
        HttpServletRequest request) {

        ErrorResponse error = ErrorResponse.builder()
            .timestamp(LocalDateTime.now())
            .status(HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR.value())
            .message("Internal server error")
            .details(ex.getMessage())
            .path(request.getRequestURI())
            .build();

        // Log for debugging
        log.error("Unhandled exception in " + request.getRequestURI(), ex);

        return new ResponseEntity<>(error, HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR);
    }
}

// Error response DTO
@Data
@Builder
public class ErrorResponse {
    private LocalDateTime timestamp;
    private int status;
    private String message;
    private String details;
    private String path;
    private Map<String, String> errors;
}

// Controller remains clean
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/payments")
public class PaymentController {

    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<PaymentResponse> create(@Valid @RequestBody PaymentRequest req) {
        // No try-catch needed - exceptions handled globally
        Payment payment = paymentService.process(req);
        return ResponseEntity.ok(new PaymentResponse(payment));
    }
}
```

**Advanced: Aspect-based logging**

```java
@Aspect
@Component
public class ExceptionLoggingAspect {

    @AfterThrowing(pointcut = "execution(* com.api.controller.*.*(..))", 
                   throwing = "ex")
    public void logException(JoinPoint jp, Exception ex) {
        log.error("Exception in {}.{}: {}",
            jp.getSignature().getDeclaringTypeName(),
            jp.getSignature().getName(),
            ex.getMessage(),
            ex);
    }
}
