Central exception handling prevents repeating error logic, ensures consistent API responses.

Spring Boot startup goes through: dependencies resolution → component scanning → bean creation → context initialization → auto-configurations applied → application ready. Auto-Configuration applies conditional beans based on classpath.

**Step-by-step flow:**

```java
// 1. SpringApplication.run() called
@SpringBootApplication // Enables auto-config
public class App {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(App.class, args);
    }
}

// 2. SpringBootApplication annotation
@SpringBootConfiguration // Enables @Configuration
@EnableAutoConfiguration  // KEY: enables auto-config
@ComponentScan           // Scans for @Component/@Service/@Repository
public @interface SpringBootApplication { }

// 3. EnableAutoConfiguration processes
// Reads META-INF/spring.factories (or spring/factories)
// List of auto-config classes:
// org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.jdbc.DataSourceAutoConfiguration
// org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.orm.jpa.HibernateJpaAutoConfiguration
// org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.web.servlet.DispatcherServletAutoConfiguration

// 4. Auto-config classes conditionally create beans
@Configuration
@ConditionalOnClass(DataSource.class) // Only if on classpath
@ConditionalOnMissingBean(DataSource.class) // Only if not already defined
public class DataSourceAutoConfiguration {

    @Bean
    public DataSource dataSource() {
        // Create default DataSource if not provided
        return new HikariDataSource(hikariConfig());
    }
}

// 5. Component scanning creates application beans
@Service
public class UserService {
    @Autowired
    private UserRepository repo; // Found via scanning
}

// 6. ApplicationContext initialization
// Calls @PostConstruct on all beans
// Fires ApplicationReadyEvent

// 7. Application is ready
System.out.println("Started in " + (System.currentTimeMillis() - startTime) + "ms");
