REST requires client-server synchronism (request-response waiting); asynchronous communication decouples them. REST is bad for: fire-and-forget operations, high latency networks, long-running tasks.

**Synchronous vs Asynchronous:**

```java
// SYNCHRONOUS (REST)
@RestController
public class OrderController {

    @PostMapping("/orders")
    public ResponseEntity<OrderResponse> createOrder(@RequestBody OrderRequest req) {
        // Client WAITS here
        Order order = orderService.create(req);

        // Process inventory, charge payment, etc.
        // All happens in this thread

        // Client gets response only when complete
        return ResponseEntity.ok(new OrderResponse(order));
    }
}

// Client code blocks waiting for response
OrderResponse response = restTemplate.postForObject(url, request, OrderResponse.class);
System.out.println("Order created: " + response.getId());
// If processing takes 30 seconds, client waits 30 seconds

// ASYNCHRONOUS (Message Queue)
@Service
public class OrderService {

    @Autowired
    private KafkaTemplate<String, OrderEvent> kafka;

    public OrderResponse createOrder(OrderRequest req) {
        // Immediate response (no waiting)
        Order order = new Order(req);
        orderRepository.save(order);

        // Publish event and return immediately
        OrderEvent event = new OrderEvent(order);
        kafka.send("order-created", event);

        return new OrderResponse(order); // Client gets response in milliseconds
    }
}

// Async processor (runs later, decoupled)
@KafkaListener(topics = "order-created")
public void processOrder(OrderEvent event) {
    // Process in background
    inventoryService.deductStock(event.getOrder());
    paymentService.charge(event.getOrder());
    shippingService.createShipment(event.getOrder());
    // Takes 30 seconds, but client doesn't care
}
```

**When REST is bad:**

```java
// Bad: Long-running payment processing
@PostMapping("/api/pay")
public ResponseEntity<PaymentResponse> pay(@RequestBody PaymentRequest req) {
    // Charges credit card (5-10 seconds)
    PaymentResult result = gateway.charge(req.getCardToken(), req.getAmount());

    // Client waits 10 seconds for response!
    // Network timeout risk increases
    // Client can't retry safely (idempotency needed)

    return ResponseEntity.ok(new PaymentResponse(result));
}

// Bad: Bulk data processing
@PostMapping("/api/users/import")
public ResponseEntity<ImportResult> importUsers(@RequestBody List<User> users) {
    // Process 100k users (5+ minutes)
    // Client times out after 30 seconds
    // Request might be retried, causing duplicates

    return ResponseEntity.ok(processAllUsers(users));
}

// Good: Asynchronous approach
@PostMapping("/api/users/import")
public ResponseEntity<JobId> importUsers(@RequestBody List<User> users) {
    // Return immediately
    String jobId = UUID.randomUUID().toString();
    asyncQueue.submit(jobId, users); // Process asynchronously

    return ResponseEntity.accepted()
        .location(URI.create("/api/jobs/" + jobId))
        .build();
}

@GetMapping("/api/jobs/{jobId}")
public ResponseEntity<JobStatus> getJobStatus(@PathVariable String jobId) {
    // Client polls for status
    JobStatus status = asyncQueue.getStatus(jobId);
    return ResponseEntity.ok(status);
}
```

**When to use what:**
- REST: Fast operations (<5 seconds)
- Async: Slow operations, fire-and-forget, decoupling critical

Circuit Breaker solves cascading failures: when a service is down, stop calling it immediately to avoid timeout storms. Instead, fast-fail and try later.

**Problem without Circuit Breaker:**

```java
// Service A calls Service B repeatedly
@Service
public class OrderService {

    @Autowired
    private RestTemplate http;

    public void processOrder(Order order) {
        try {
            // Service B is DOWN
            PaymentResponse response = http.postForObject(
                "http://payment-service/charge",
                order,
                PaymentResponse.class
            );
            // Timeout: waits 30 seconds
            // Then throws TimeoutException
        } catch (Exception e) {
            log.error("Payment failed", e);
            // Order processing fails
        }

        // If 1000 concurrent requests arrive:
        // Each waits 30 seconds -> thread pool exhausted
        // -> Entire service becomes unresponsive
        // -> Cascading failure to upstream services
    }
}
```

**Solution with Circuit Breaker:**

```java
@Service
public class OrderServiceWithCircuitBreaker {

    @Autowired
    private Resilience4j circuitBreaker;

    @CircuitBreaker(name = "payment-service", fallbackMethod = "paymentFallback")
    public PaymentResponse chargePayment(Order order) {
        // Calls payment service through circuit breaker
        return paymentService.charge(order);
    }

    // Fallback when circuit is OPEN
    public PaymentResponse paymentFallback(Order order, Exception e) {
        log.warn("Payment service unavailable, queuing for retry");

        // Queue order for later processing
        retryQueue.add(order);

        // Return synthetic response
        return PaymentResponse.pending();
    }
}

// Circuit Breaker states:
// 1. CLOSED: Normal operation, calls go through
// 2. OPEN: Service detected as down, calls immediately fail
// 3. HALF_OPEN: Testing if service recovered, allows limited calls

// Configuration
@Configuration
public class CircuitBreakerConfig {

    @Bean
    public CircuitBreakerRegistry circuitBreakerRegistry() {
        return CircuitBreakerRegistry.of(
            CircuitBreakerConfig.custom()
                .failureRateThreshold(50) // 50% failures -> open
                .slowCallRateThreshold(50) // 50% slow calls -> open
                .slowCallDurationThreshold(Duration.ofSeconds(5))
                .waitDurationInOpenState(Duration.ofSeconds(30)) // Try again after 30s
                .permittedNumberOfCallsInHalfOpenState(3) // Test with 3 calls
                .build()
        );
    }
}
```

**Real behavior:**

```
Time 0:00 - Payment service crashes
          CLOSED -> OPEN (after failure threshold reached)

Time 0:01 - Requests arrive
          Circuit is OPEN
          paymentFallback() called immediately
          No timeout, instant response
          Orders queued for retry

Time 0:30 - Interval passed
          OPEN -> HALF_OPEN
          3 test requests sent to payment service

Time 0:31 - Payment service recovered
          HALF_OPEN -> CLOSED
          Normal operation resumes
          Queued orders retried
```

Circuit Breaker prevents timeout storms and allows services to gracefully degrade.

Idempotency means the same operation produces the same result whether executed once or multiple times. Critical for handling retries safely.

**Payment system example:**

```java
// WRONG: Not idempotent
@PostMapping("/api/payments")
public ResponseEntity<PaymentResponse> pay(@RequestBody PaymentRequest req) {
    // Customer's network dies after payment succeeds but before response
    // Customer doesn't know if payment went through
    // Retries the request
    // Second payment goes through -> DOUBLE CHARGE!

    Account account = accountRepo.findById(req.getAccountId());
    account.debit(req.getAmount());
    accountRepo.save(account);

    // Problem: Same request causes same debit twice
    return ResponseEntity.ok(new PaymentResponse("success"));
}

// CORRECT: Idempotent
@PostMapping("/api/payments")
public ResponseEntity<PaymentResponse> pay(@RequestBody PaymentRequest req) {
    // Use idempotency key (unique identifier for this operation)
    String idempotencyKey = req.getIdempotencyKey(); // Client provides

    // Check if we already processed this payment
    Payment existingPayment = paymentRepo.findByIdempotencyKey(idempotencyKey);
    if (existingPayment != null) {
        // Return cached response - same request -> same response
        return ResponseEntity.ok(
            new PaymentResponse(existingPayment.getId(), existingPayment.getStatus())
        );
    }

    // First time: process payment
    Account account = accountRepo.findById(req.getAccountId());
    account.debit(req.getAmount());
    accountRepo.save(account);

    Payment payment = new Payment(idempotencyKey, account, req.getAmount());
    paymentRepo.save(payment);

    return ResponseEntity.ok(new PaymentResponse(payment.getId(), "SUCCESS"));
}

// Client side
String idempotencyKey = UUID.randomUUID().toString();
PaymentRequest request = new PaymentRequest();
request.setIdempotencyKey(idempotencyKey);

// First attempt
ResponseEntity<PaymentResponse> response1 = restTemplate.postForEntity(url, request, PaymentResponse.class);
// Network fails

// Retry with SAME idempotency key
ResponseEntity<PaymentResponse> response2 = restTemplate.postForEntity(url, request, PaymentResponse.class);
// Same response returned, no double charge!
```

**Idempotency implementation patterns:**

```java
// Pattern 1: Database uniqueness constraint
@Entity
class Payment {
    @Column(unique = true)
    String idempotencyKey; // Prevents duplicates at DB level

    String status;
    double amount;
}

// Pattern 2: Cache with TTL
@Service
public class IdempotentPaymentService {
    @Autowired
    private RedisTemplate<String, PaymentResponse> cache;

    public PaymentResponse processPayment(PaymentRequest req) {
        String key = "payment:" + req.getIdempotencyKey();

        // Check cache first
        PaymentResponse cached = cache.opsForValue().get(key);
        if (cached != null) {
            return cached; // Return cached response
        }

        // Process payment
        PaymentResponse response = reallyProcessPayment(req);

        // Cache for 24 hours
        cache.opsForValue().set(key, response, Duration.ofHours(24));
        return response;
    }
}

// Pattern 3: Event sourcing
@Service
public class EventSourcedPaymentService {

    public PaymentResponse processPayment(PaymentRequest req) {
        String idempotencyKey = req.getIdempotencyKey();

        // Check if event already stored
        PaymentEvent existing = eventStore.findByIdempotencyKey(idempotencyKey);
        if (existing != null) {
            return existing.getResponse();
        }

        // Create and store event
        PaymentEvent event = new PaymentEvent(idempotencyKey, req);
        eventStore.save(event); // Immutable log

        // Apply event
        Account account = accountRepo.findById(req.getAccountId());
        account.applyPaymentEvent(event);
        accountRepo.save(account);

        return event.getResponse();
    }
}
```

Idempotency is mandatory for distributed systems where retries are inevitable.

