API versioning strategies: URI path versioning (/v1/, /v2/), query parameters, custom headers, content negotiation. Each has trade-offs.

**Common strategies:**

```java
// Strategy 1: URI Path Versioning (most common)
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/v1/orders")
public class OrderControllerV1 {

    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<OrderResponseV1> create(@RequestBody OrderRequestV1 req) {
        // V1 response format
        return ResponseEntity.ok(new OrderResponseV1(/* ... */));
    }
}

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/v2/orders")
public class OrderControllerV2 {

    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<OrderResponseV2> create(@RequestBody OrderRequestV2 req) {
        // V2 has new fields: discountCode, loyaltyPoints
        return ResponseEntity.ok(new OrderResponseV2(/* ... */));
    }
}

// Pros: Explicit, easy to maintain, backwards compatible
// Cons: Duplicate code, multiple endpoints

// Strategy 2: Request Header Versioning
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/orders")
public class OrderController {

    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<?> create(
        @RequestBody OrderRequest req,
        @RequestHeader(value = "X-API-Version", defaultValue = "1") int version) {

        if (version == 1) {
            return ResponseEntity.ok(createV1Response(req));
        } else if (version == 2) {
            return ResponseEntity.ok(createV2Response(req));
        }
    }
}

// Usage: curl -H "X-API-Version: 2" http://api.com/orders
// Pros: Single endpoint, cleaner URLs
// Cons: Version hidden in headers, harder to debug

// Strategy 3: Accept Header / Content Negotiation
@RestController
public class OrderController {

    @PostMapping(value = "/orders", 
                 consumes = "application/vnd.company.v1+json")
    public ResponseEntity<OrderResponseV1> createV1(@RequestBody OrderRequestV1 req) {
        // V1: consumes application/vnd.company.v1+json
        return ResponseEntity.ok(new OrderResponseV1(req));
    }

    @PostMapping(value = "/orders",
                 consumes = "application/vnd.company.v2+json")
    public ResponseEntity<OrderResponseV2> createV2(@RequestBody OrderRequestV2 req) {
        // V2: consumes application/vnd.company.v2+json
        return ResponseEntity.ok(new OrderResponseV2(req));
    }
}

// Usage: 
// curl -H "Content-Type: application/vnd.company.v1+json" -d @order.json http://api.com/orders
// curl -H "Content-Type: application/vnd.company.v2+json" -d @order.json http://api.com/orders

// Strategy 4: Query Parameter Versioning
@GetMapping("/orders")
public ResponseEntity<?> getOrders(
    @RequestParam(defaultValue = "1") int version) {

    if (version == 1) {
        // V1 response
    } else if (version == 2) {
        // V2 response
    }
}

// Usage: GET /api/orders?version=2
```

**Deprecation and migration:**

```java
// Mark old versions as deprecated
@Deprecated
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/v1/orders")
public class OrderControllerV1 {

    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<OrderResponseV1> create(@RequestBody OrderRequestV1 req) {
        log.warn("Using deprecated API v1. Please migrate to /api/v2/");
        return ResponseEntity.ok(new OrderResponseV1(req));
    }
}

// Sunset old versions
@Component
public class APIVersionFilter implements Filter {

    @Override
    public void doFilter(ServletRequest request, ServletResponse response, 
                        FilterChain chain) throws IOException, ServletException {
        HttpServletRequest httpRequest = (HttpServletRequest) request;
        String path = httpRequest.getRequestURI();

        // Block v1 after sunset date
        if (path.contains("/v1/") && LocalDate.now().isAfter(SUNSET_DATE)) {
            ((HttpServletResponse) response).sendError(
                HttpStatus.GONE.value(),
                "API v1 has been deprecated. Use /api/v2/"
            );
            return;
        }

        chain.doFilter(request, response);
    }
}
```

**Best practice:**
- Use URI versioning for major changes
- Use headers for minor variations
- Maintain 2 versions simultaneously during migration
- Set sunset dates and communicate deprecation

N+1 problem: Query returns 1 parent, then triggers N queries for children instead of 1 JOIN. Classic ORM pitfall with massive performance impact.

**The problem:**

```java
@Entity
class Order {
    @OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.LAZY) // Default
    List<LineItem> items;
}

@Entity
class LineItem {
    Long orderId;
}

// N+1 example:
List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findAll(); // 1 query: SELECT * FROM orders

for (Order order : orders) {
    List<LineItem> items = order.getItems(); // N queries: SELECT * FROM line_items WHERE order_id = ?
    for (LineItem item : items) {
        System.out.println(item.getProductName());
    }
}

// For 100 orders: 1 + 100 = 101 queries!
// Database gets hammered, huge latency
```

**Detection:**

```java
// Enable SQL logging
spring.jpa.show-sql=true
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.format_sql=true
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.use_sql_comments=true

// Output shows:
// Hibernate: SELECT o.* FROM orders o
// Hibernate: SELECT li.* FROM line_items li WHERE li.order_id = 1
// Hibernate: SELECT li.* FROM line_items li WHERE li.order_id = 2
// ... repeated 100 times

// Profiler also shows excessive DB round-trips
```

**Solutions:**

```java
// Solution 1: Eager loading
@Entity
class Order {
    @OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.EAGER) // JOINS automatically
    List<LineItem> items;
}

List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findAll();
// Single query with JOIN - 1 query!

// But EAGER has problems:
// - Cartesian product (100 orders × 10 items = 1000 rows)
// - Can't use EAGER for multiple relationships

// Solution 2: Explicit JOIN FETCH (preferred)
@Repository
public interface OrderRepository extends JpaRepository<Order, Long> {

    @Query("SELECT o FROM Order o JOIN FETCH o.items i")
    List<Order> findAllWithItems();
}

List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findAllWithItems();
// Single query with JOIN - clean and performant

// Solution 3: Projection (only fetch what you need)
@Repository
public interface OrderRepository extends JpaRepository<Order, Long> {

    @Query("""SELECT new OrderDTO(o.id, o.date, COUNT(i.id))
              FROM Order o
              LEFT JOIN o.items i
              GROUP BY o.id""")
    List<OrderDTO> findOrderStats();
}

// Solution 4: Separate queries (when JOINs are complex)
@Repository
public interface OrderRepository extends JpaRepository<Order, Long> {

    @Query("SELECT o FROM Order o WHERE o.date > ?1")
    List<Order> findRecentOrders(LocalDate since);

    @Query("""SELECT i FROM LineItem i WHERE i.orderId IN ?1""")
    List<LineItem> findItemsForOrders(List<Long> orderIds);
}

// Usage: Reduce N+1 to 2 queries
List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findRecentOrders(LocalDate.now());
List<LineItem> items = orderRepository.findItemsForOrders(
    orders.stream().map(Order::getId).collect(toList())
);

// Solution 5: Batch fetching (Hibernate optimization)
// application.yml
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.default_batch_fetch_size=20

// Instead of 100 queries, Hibernate batches:
// SELECT * FROM line_items WHERE order_id IN (1,2,3,...,20)
// SELECT * FROM line_items WHERE order_id IN (21,22,23,...,40)
// ... etc
```

N+1 is a classic interview question because it reveals ORM understanding. Always profile queries in development.

Lazy loading defers fetching until accessed (better for large datasets, avoids unnecessary queries); Eager loading fetches immediately (fewer queries, cartesian product risk).

**Impact and trade-offs:**

```java
@Entity
class Customer {
    String name;

    @OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.LAZY) // Default
    List<Order> orders;
}

// LAZY example:
Customer customer = customerRepository.findById(1);
// Query: SELECT * FROM customers WHERE id = 1
// orders NOT fetched yet

if (customer.getOrders().size() > 0) {
    // Query: SELECT * FROM orders WHERE customer_id = 1
    // LAZY triggered when accessing orders
}

// EAGER example:
@Entity
class Customer {
    @OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.EAGER)
    List<Order> orders;
}

Customer customer = customerRepository.findById(1);
// Query: SELECT c.*, o.* FROM customers c
//        LEFT JOIN orders o ON c.id = o.customer_id
// orders fetched immediately

// Problem with EAGER: Cartesian product
// Customer with 5 orders: 5 duplicate rows returned
// Customer with 20 orders: 20 duplicate rows
// Scales poorly
```

**Real production scenarios:**

```java
// Scenario 1: REST endpoint returns customer
@GetMapping("/customers/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<CustomerDTO> getCustomer(@PathVariable Long id) {
    Customer customer = customerRepository.findById(id).orElseThrow();

    // If orders is LAZY: 2 queries total (good)
    // If orders is EAGER: unnecessary overhead when only customer data needed

    return ResponseEntity.ok(CustomerDTO.from(customer));
}

// Scenario 2: List all customers with orders
@GetMapping("/customers")
public ResponseEntity<List<CustomerDTO>> listCustomers() {
    List<Customer> customers = customerRepository.findAll();
    // LAZY: 101 queries (1 for customers, 100 for orders) - N+1!
    // EAGER: 1 query with JOIN, but 5000 rows if average 50 orders/customer

    return ResponseEntity.ok(customers.stream()
        .map(CustomerDTO::from)
        .collect(toList()));
}

// Scenario 3: Complex analytics query
@GetMapping("/reports/customer-orders")
public ResponseEntity<List<CustomerOrderReport>> getReport() {
    List<Customer> customers = customerRepository.findAllWithOrders();
    // Use explicit JOIN FETCH instead of EAGER
    // Gives you control when data is large

    return ResponseEntity.ok(generateReport(customers));
}
```

**Best practices:**

```java
// DON'T use EAGER by default
@Entity
class Order {
    @OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.EAGER) // WRONG
    List<Shipment> shipments;

    @OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.EAGER) // WRONG - can't have multiple EAGERs
    List<Payment> payments;
}

// DO use explicit JOIN FETCH in queries
@Repository
public interface OrderRepository extends JpaRepository<Order, Long> {

    @Query("SELECT o FROM Order o " +
           "JOIN FETCH o.shipments " +
           "JOIN FETCH o.payments " +
           "WHERE o.id = ?1")
    Optional<Order> findWithDetails(Long id);

    @Query("SELECT o FROM Order o")
    Page<Order> findAllWithoutDetails(Pageable page);
}

// DO profile and measure
// Development: Lazy = 101 queries, but each fast
// Development: Eager = 1 query, but 5000 rows returned
// Production: Network latency changes calculus

// DON'T load relationships you don't need
List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findAll();
// If you only access order.getId(), don't eager-load shipments
```

Wrong choice between lazy/eager can cause either N+1 disaster or memory bloat.

Database index is NOT used when: non-indexed columns, column functions, type mismatches, OR conditions with non-indexed columns, incorrect query hints, or poor statistics.

**Examples of index bypass:**

```java
// Assuming we have: CREATE INDEX idx_user_email ON users(email)

// 1. Using function on indexed column
SELECT * FROM users WHERE UPPER(email) = 'ALICE@EXAMPLE.COM';
// Index NOT used: function call prevents index usage
// MySQL must scan entire table and apply UPPER()

// Solution: Use indexed value
SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = 'alice@example.com';
// Index USED

// 2. Type mismatch
CREATE TABLE orders (
    id INT,
    customer_id INT,
    created_at INT // Stored as Unix timestamp
);
CREATE INDEX idx_customer_id ON orders(customer_id);

// Type mismatch: VARCHAR passed to INT column
SELECT * FROM orders WHERE customer_id = '5'; // String '5'
// Index MAY be bypassed due to type casting

// Solution: Use correct type
SELECT * FROM orders WHERE customer_id = 5; // Integer 5
// Index used reliably

// 3. OR with mix of indexed/non-indexed
CREATE INDEX idx_status ON orders(status);
-- No index on created_at

SELECT * FROM orders WHERE status = 'PENDING' OR created_at > 1699000000;
-- Index NOT used: OR forces full table scan
-- Can't use index for partial condition

// Solution: Use UNION with separate indexes
(SELECT * FROM orders WHERE status = 'PENDING')
UNION
(SELECT * FROM orders WHERE created_at > 1699000000);

// 4. LIKE pattern without prefix
CREATE INDEX idx_email ON users(email);

SELECT * FROM users WHERE email LIKE '%@example.com';
// Index NOT used: leading wildcard bypasses index

SELECT * FROM users WHERE email LIKE 'alice%';
// Index USED: prefix is fixed

// 5. Incorrect statistics
ANALYZE TABLE orders;
-- MySQL rebuild index statistics
-- Old stats might cause optimizer to choose full scan

// 6. OR with too many options
SELECT * FROM orders WHERE customer_id IN (1,2,3,...,1000);
-- Optimizer might choose full scan over index
```

**Java/JPA perspective:**

```java
@Entity
class Order {

    @Column(name = "email")
    String email;

    @Column(name = "status")
    String status;

    @Column(name = "created_at")
    LocalDateTime createdAt;
}

// These queries won't use indexes effectively:

// Bad 1: Function on indexed column
@Query("SELECT o FROM Order o WHERE UPPER(o.email) = ?1")
List<Order> findByEmailIgnoreCase(String email); // Index not used!

// Better
@Query("SELECT o FROM Order o WHERE o.email = ?1")
List<Order> findByEmail(String email); // Index used

// Bad 2: LIKE with wildcard
@Query("SELECT o FROM Order o WHERE o.email LIKE '%' || ?1 || '%'")
List<Order> findByEmailContains(String term);

// Better: Use LIKE with prefix only or full-text search
@Query("SELECT o FROM Order o WHERE o.email LIKE ?1 || '%'")
List<Order> findByEmailStartsWith(String term);

// Bad 3: OR conditions
@Query("SELECT o FROM Order o WHERE o.status = ?1 OR o.email = ?2")
List<Order> findByStatusOrEmail(String status, String email);

// Better: Union queries if both are indexed
List<Order> findByStatus(String status); // Indexed
List<Order> findByEmail(String email);   // Indexed
// App combines results
```

Interviews test knowledge of when DB optimizations fail. Always think about index usage.

Optimistic locking (version column, optimistic exceptions) assumes conflicts rare and checks on commit; Pessimistic locking (SELECT FOR UPDATE) locks immediately.

**Comparison:**

```java
// Optimistic Locking: Version-based conflict detection
@Entity
class Account {
    Long id;
    BigDecimal balance;

    @Version // Optimistic lock column
    Long version; // Incremented on every update
}

@Service
public class TransferService {

    @Transactional
    public void transfer(Long from, Long to, BigDecimal amount) {
        Account fromAccount = accountRepository.findById(from).orElseThrow();
        // version = 5

        Account toAccount = accountRepository.findById(to).orElseThrow();
        // version = 10

        // Simulate another thread updating fromAccount
        // (in real scenario: concurrent transaction)
        // SELECT ... FROM accounts WHERE id = from FOR UPDATE;

        fromAccount.setBalance(fromAccount.getBalance().subtract(amount));
        toAccount.setBalance(toAccount.getBalance().add(amount));

        accountRepository.save(fromAccount); // version = 6
        accountRepository.save(toAccount);   // version = 11
    }
}

// If another transaction modified fromAccount:
// UPDATE accounts SET balance = ?, version = 6 WHERE id = ? AND version = 5
// -- Fails if version != 5
// Throws OptimisticLockingException
// Application retries the entire transfer

// Pessimistic Locking: Lock immediately
@Repository
public interface AccountRepository extends JpaRepository<Account, Long> {

    @Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE)
    @Query("SELECT a FROM Account a WHERE a.id = ?1")
    Account findByIdForUpdate(Long id);
}

@Service
public class TransferService {

    @Transactional
    public void transfer(Long from, Long to, BigDecimal amount) {
        // SELECT ... FROM accounts WHERE id = ? FOR UPDATE
        // -- Lock acquired immediately
        Account fromAccount = accountRepository.findByIdForUpdate(from);
        // Other transactions WAIT here until lock released

        // SELECT ... FROM accounts WHERE id = ? FOR UPDATE
        Account toAccount = accountRepository.findByIdForUpdate(to);
        // Lock acquired on both accounts

        // Do transfer (no other thread can modify these rows)
        fromAccount.setBalance(fromAccount.getBalance().subtract(amount));
        toAccount.setBalance(toAccount.getBalance().add(amount));

        accountRepository.save(fromAccount);
        accountRepository.save(toAccount);
    }
    // Locks released on transaction commit
}
```

**When to use which:**

```java
// Use OPTIMISTIC when:
// - Conflicts are rare (reads much more than writes)
// - Can tolerate retry logic
// - High concurrency (many readers, few writers)
// - Non-blocking desired

@Entity
class BlogPost {
    @Version
    Long version;

    String title;
    String content;
    Long views;
}

// View count frequently updated, but edit conflicts rare
// Optimistic: many concurrent reads, occasional write
// If write conflicts with read: retry

// Use PESSIMISTIC when:
// - Conflicts are frequent (many concurrent updates)
// - Can't tolerate retries
// - Business logic requires serialization
// - Small subset of critical data

@Service
public class PaymentProcessor {

    @Transactional
    public void processPayment(Long accountId, BigDecimal amount) {
        // CRITICAL: Must execute atomically, no conflicts
        // SELECT ... FROM accounts WHERE id = ? FOR UPDATE
        Account account = accountRepository.findByIdForUpdate(accountId);

        if (account.getBalance() < amount) {
            throw new InsufficientFundsException();
        }

        account.debit(amount);
        accountRepository.save(account);

        // Lock held until commit - no other transaction can update
    }
}
```

**Performance implications:**

```
Optimistic:
- No locks held
- High throughput under low contention
- Retry overhead if conflicts occur
- Good for: reading, occasional updates

Pessimistic:
- Locks held for transaction duration
- Other transactions wait
- Lower throughput under high contention
- Good for: critical operations, frequent conflicts
```

Choice depends on conflict patterns and business requirements.

For very large tables: keyset pagination (cursor-based), limit+offset with indexed sort, or sharding. Avoid OFFSET for massive datasets—it's O(n).

**Methods:**

```java
// WRONG: Offset-based (SLOW)
@GetMapping("/orders")
public ResponseEntity<Page<Order>> getOrders(@RequestParam int page) {
    // Page 1 (offset 0): SELECT ... LIMIT 20
    // Page 100 (offset 1980): SELECT ... LIMIT 20 OFFSET 1980
    // Database still scans first 1980 rows, very slow!

    Pageable pageable = PageRequest.of(page, 20, Sort.by("id").descending());
    Page<Order> orders = orderRepository.findAll(pageable);
    return ResponseEntity.ok(orders);
}

// Benchmark
// Page 1: 10ms
// Page 100: 500ms
// Page 1000: 5 seconds (OFFSET scans through 20k rows!)

// CORRECT: Keyset pagination (cursor-based)
@GetMapping("/orders")
public ResponseEntity<List<OrderDTO>> getOrders(
    @RequestParam(required = false) Long lastId) {

    if (lastId == null) {
        lastId = Long.MAX_VALUE; // First page
    }

    // WHERE id < lastId ORDER BY id DESC LIMIT 21
    // Uses index on ID, scans in order
    List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findByIdLessThanOrderByIdDesc(lastId, PageRequest.of(0, 21));

    List<OrderDTO> results = orders.stream()
        .limit(20)
        .map(OrderDTO::from)
        .collect(toList());

    boolean hasMore = orders.size() > 20;
    Long nextLastId = hasMore ? orders.get(20).getId() : null;

    // Return results + cursor for next page
    Map<String, Object> response = Map.of(
        "orders", results,
        "nextCursor", nextLastId
    );

    return ResponseEntity.ok(response);
}

// Benchmark
// Page 1: 10ms (index scan)
// Page 100: 8ms (same index scan, just different startpoint)
// Page 1000: 7ms (still index scan, no offset!)

// Repository
@Repository
public interface OrderRepository extends JpaRepository<Order, Long> {

    List<Order> findByIdLessThanOrderByIdDesc(Long id, Pageable page);
}

// CORRECT: Timestamp-based pagination
@GetMapping("/orders/by-date")
public ResponseEntity<List<OrderDTO>> getOrdersByDate(
    @RequestParam(required = false) LocalDateTime lastCreatedAt) {

    if (lastCreatedAt == null) {
        lastCreatedAt = LocalDateTime.now();
    }

    // WHERE created_at < ? ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT 21
    List<Order> orders = orderRepository
        .findByCreatedAtLessThanOrderByCreatedAtDesc(lastCreatedAt, PageRequest.of(0, 21));

    List<OrderDTO> results = orders.stream()
        .limit(20)
        .map(OrderDTO::from)
        .collect(toList());

    LocalDateTime nextLastCreatedAt = orders.size() > 20 ? orders.get(20).getCreatedAt() : null;

    return ResponseEntity.ok(Map.of(
        "orders", results,
        "nextCursor", nextLastCreatedAt
    ));
}

// SCALABLE: Sharded pagination
// For table with billions of rows: partition by key
@Service
public class ShardedOrderService {

    public List<Order> getOrders(int page, int pageSize) {
        // Determine shard based on customer_id
        int shardId = customerId % NUM_SHARDS;

        // Query specific shard
        List<Order> orders = shardedRepository.getOrders(shardId, page, pageSize);

        return orders;
    }
}
```

Keyset pagination is mandatory for large-scale systems.

A wallet transfer system must guarantee that money is never lost, duplicated, or left in a half-applied state. The core challenge is achieving atomicity across two account mutations while surviving failures at any point.

**Core invariant:** debit(A) + credit(B) must be atomic. If either step fails, neither should persist.

**Database-level design (single-service):**

```java
@Entity
public class Wallet {
    @Id
    private Long id;
    private BigDecimal balance;

    @Version
    private Long version; // Optimistic lock
}

@Entity
public class Transfer {
    @Id
    private String id; // idempotency key (UUID from client)
    private Long fromWalletId;
    private Long toWalletId;
    private BigDecimal amount;
    private TransferStatus status; // PENDING, COMPLETED, FAILED
    private Instant createdAt;
}

@Service
public class WalletService {

    @Transactional(isolation = Isolation.READ_COMMITTED)
    public Transfer transfer(String idempotencyKey, Long from, Long to, BigDecimal amount) {
        // 1. Idempotency check — return existing result on retry
        Transfer existing = transferRepo.findById(idempotencyKey).orElse(null);
        if (existing != null) return existing;

        // 2. Lock both wallets in a consistent order to prevent deadlocks
        //    Always acquire lower-ID lock first
        Long firstId  = Math.min(from, to);
        Long secondId = Math.max(from, to);
        Wallet w1 = walletRepo.findByIdWithLock(firstId);  // SELECT … FOR UPDATE
        Wallet w2 = walletRepo.findByIdWithLock(secondId);

        Wallet sender   = (w1.getId().equals(from)) ? w1 : w2;
        Wallet receiver = (w1.getId().equals(to))   ? w1 : w2;

        // 3. Business validation
        if (sender.getBalance().compareTo(amount) < 0)
            throw new InsufficientFundsException("Insufficient balance");

        // 4. Mutate balances
        sender.setBalance(sender.getBalance().subtract(amount));
        receiver.setBalance(receiver.getBalance().add(amount));
        walletRepo.save(sender);
        walletRepo.save(receiver);

        // 5. Persist transfer record atomically in same transaction
        Transfer transfer = Transfer.builder()
            .id(idempotencyKey)
            .fromWalletId(from)
            .toWalletId(to)
            .amount(amount)
            .status(TransferStatus.COMPLETED)
            .createdAt(Instant.now())
            .build();
        return transferRepo.save(transfer);
    }
}

@Repository
public interface WalletRepository extends JpaRepository<Wallet, Long> {
    @Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE)
    @Query("SELECT w FROM Wallet w WHERE w.id = :id")
    Wallet findByIdWithLock(@Param("id") Long id);
}
```

**Deadlock prevention — always acquire locks in the same order:**

```
Thread 1: lock wallet-1, lock wallet-2  (transfer A -> B)
Thread 2: lock wallet-1, lock wallet-2  (transfer B -> A)
             ↑ same order = no circular wait = no deadlock
```

**Distributed design (wallets in separate services):**

When wallets live in different microservices, a single DB transaction is impossible. Use the **Saga pattern** with compensating transactions:

```
Step 1: DebitService.debit(from, amount)   -> publishes DEBITED event
Step 2: CreditService.credit(to, amount)   -> publishes CREDITED event

On failure at Step 2:
Compensation: DebitService.refund(from, amount) -> reverses Step 1
```

```java
// Orchestration-based Saga
@Service
public class TransferSaga {

    public void execute(TransferCommand cmd) {
        String sagaId = UUID.randomUUID().toString();
        sagaStore.save(new SagaState(sagaId, "STARTED"));

        try {
            debitService.debit(sagaId, cmd.getFrom(), cmd.getAmount());
            sagaStore.update(sagaId, "DEBITED");

            creditService.credit(sagaId, cmd.getTo(), cmd.getAmount());
            sagaStore.update(sagaId, "COMPLETED");

        } catch (CreditFailedException e) {
            // Compensate: reverse the debit
            debitService.refund(sagaId, cmd.getFrom(), cmd.getAmount());
            sagaStore.update(sagaId, "ROLLED_BACK");
            throw new TransferFailedException("Credit failed, debit reversed", e);
        }
    }
}
```

**Production safeguards:**
- Every transfer gets a client-supplied idempotency key (UUID) to prevent double-charges on network retry.
- All balance mutations are append-only ledger entries (never UPDATE balance directly) — audit trail is free.
- Reconciliation job runs nightly: sum of all debit events must equal sum of all credit events.
- Alert when `PENDING` transfers are older than 5 minutes — saga may be stuck.

**ASCII flow:**
```
Client
  │  POST /transfer {idempotencyKey, from, to, amount}
  ▼
WalletService
  ├─ idempotency check (return early if duplicate)
  ├─ acquire DB locks (low-ID first)
  ├─ validate balance
  ├─ debit sender
  ├─ credit receiver
  └─ persist Transfer record (same TX)
  ▼
Client ← 200 OK {transferId, status: COMPLETED}
```

Scaling a high-traffic API is a layered problem. No single technique is sufficient — you must eliminate bottlenecks at each layer: network, application, database, and data locality.

**Layer 1 — Horizontal scaling (stateless services)**

The application must be stateless so any instance can handle any request:

```java
// BAD: In-memory state (breaks horizontal scaling)
@RestController
public class CounterController {
    private int requestCount = 0; // Each instance has its OWN counter!

    @GetMapping("/count")
    public int count() { return ++requestCount; }
}

// GOOD: Externalize state to Redis
@RestController
public class CounterController {
    @Autowired
    private StringRedisTemplate redis;

    @GetMapping("/count")
    public Long count() {
        return redis.opsForValue().increment("global:request-count");
    }
}
```

Deploy behind a load balancer (NGINX, AWS ALB) and auto-scale based on CPU/request-rate metrics.

**Layer 2 — Caching (eliminate repeated DB calls)**

```java
@Service
public class ProductService {

    @Autowired
    private RedisTemplate<String, Product> cache;

    @Autowired
    private ProductRepository db;

    public Product getProduct(Long id) {
        String key = "product:" + id;

        // Cache-aside pattern
        Product cached = cache.opsForValue().get(key);
        if (cached != null) return cached;

        Product product = db.findById(id).orElseThrow();
        cache.opsForValue().set(key, product, Duration.ofMinutes(10));
        return product;
    }

    public void updateProduct(Product p) {
        db.save(p);
        cache.delete("product:" + p.getId()); // Invalidate on write
    }
}
```

**Layer 3 — Database read replicas**

```java
// Route reads to replicas, writes to primary
@Configuration
public class DataSourceConfig {

    @Bean
    @Primary
    public DataSource primaryDataSource() {
        return buildDataSource("jdbc:mysql://primary-db:3306/app");
    }

    @Bean("replicaDataSource")
    public DataSource replicaDataSource() {
        return buildDataSource("jdbc:mysql://replica-db:3306/app");
    }
}

@Service
public class OrderService {

    @Autowired
    private OrderRepository primaryRepo;

    @Autowired
    @Qualifier("replicaOrderRepo")
    private OrderRepository replicaRepo;

    @Transactional // Goes to primary
    public Order createOrder(OrderRequest req) {
        return primaryRepo.save(new Order(req));
    }

    @Transactional(readOnly = true) // Goes to replica
    public List<Order> listOrders(Long customerId) {
        return replicaRepo.findByCustomerId(customerId);
    }
}
```

**Layer 4 — Async processing for slow operations**

```java
@RestController
public class ReportController {

    @Autowired
    private KafkaTemplate<String, ReportRequest> kafka;

    // Slow: report generation takes 30 seconds
    // BAD: synchronous — blocks thread and client
    // @PostMapping("/reports") public Report generate(...) { ... }

    // GOOD: Accept and return job ID immediately
    @PostMapping("/reports")
    public ResponseEntity<Map<String, String>> requestReport(
            @RequestBody ReportRequest req) {
        String jobId = UUID.randomUUID().toString();
        req.setJobId(jobId);
        kafka.send("report-requests", req);
        return ResponseEntity.accepted()
            .body(Map.of("jobId", jobId, "statusUrl", "/reports/" + jobId));
    }

    @GetMapping("/reports/{jobId}")
    public ResponseEntity<ReportStatus> getStatus(@PathVariable String jobId) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(reportStatusService.get(jobId));
    }
}
```

**Layer 5 — Rate limiting & back-pressure**

Protect the system from being overwhelmed (see the rate limiting question for full implementation).

**Layer 6 — Connection pooling**

```yaml
# application.yml — HikariCP tuning
spring:
  datasource:
    hikari:
      maximum-pool-size: 20       # Match DB thread count
      minimum-idle: 5
      connection-timeout: 3000    # Fail fast, don't queue requests
      idle-timeout: 600000
      max-lifetime: 1800000
```

**Scaling checklist:**

```
Traffic spike detected
   │
   ├─ Is it cacheable?  → Add Redis cache
   ├─ Is it DB reads?   → Add read replicas
   ├─ Is it slow ops?   → Move to async queue
   ├─ Is it CPU-bound?  → Horizontal scale (add instances)
   └─ Is it DB writes?  → Shard or partition the table
```

**Real numbers to know:** A single Redis node handles 100k ops/sec. A single MySQL node saturates around 5-10k complex queries/sec. A Spring Boot instance on 2 vCPUs handles ~2-3k req/sec for lightweight endpoints. These numbers guide when to add each layer.

Caching is one of the most overused tools in software engineering. Developers reach for it as a default performance fix, but it introduces a new category of hard-to-debug bugs and failure modes. Knowing when NOT to cache is as important as knowing when to cache.

**Scenario 1: Stale data causes wrong business decisions**

```java
// Inventory service caches stock counts for 10 minutes
@Service
public class InventoryService {

    @Cacheable(value = "stock", key = "#productId")
    public int getStock(Long productId) {
        return inventoryRepo.findStock(productId); // Cached for 10 min
    }
}

// Problem:
// 09:00 — Cache loaded: Product A has 5 units in stock
// 09:03 — 5 customers buy Product A simultaneously (stock now = 0)
// 09:07 — 3 more customers see 'In Stock' (stale cache) and place orders
// 09:10 — Cache expires, stock reads 0
// Result: 3 oversold orders that can't be fulfilled

// Fix: Use cache only for non-critical reads, or set very short TTL
// Better: Invalidate cache immediately on write
@CacheEvict(value = "stock", key = "#productId")
public void decrementStock(Long productId, int quantity) {
    inventoryRepo.decrementStock(productId, quantity);
}
```

**Scenario 2: Cache thundering herd (stampede)**

```java
// TTL of 1 hour set on popular product list
// At exactly 14:00, cache expires
// 5,000 simultaneous requests all miss cache and hit the DB
// DB gets 5,000 heavy queries in 1 second → DB crash

// Harmful pattern:
@Cacheable(value = "topProducts", key = "'homepage'")  // All users share same key
public List<Product> getTopProducts() {
    return db.findTop100Products(); // 500ms query
}

// Fix 1: Jitter on TTL (randomize expiry)
Duration ttl = Duration.ofMinutes(55 + ThreadLocalRandom.current().nextInt(10));
cache.opsForValue().set("topProducts", products, ttl);

// Fix 2: Probabilistic early expiration (re-cache before expiry)
public List<Product> getTopProducts() {
    String key = "topProducts";
    Long ttlSeconds = cache.getExpire(key);
    if (ttlSeconds != null && ttlSeconds < 60) {
        // Less than 1 min left → refresh proactively
        refreshCache(key);
    }
    return cache.opsForValue().get(key);
}

// Fix 3: Mutex / single-flight pattern
public List<Product> getTopProducts() {
    List<Product> cached = cache.opsForValue().get("topProducts");
    if (cached != null) return cached;

    // Only one thread computes; others wait
    synchronized (this) {
        cached = cache.opsForValue().get("topProducts"); // Double-check
        if (cached != null) return cached;

        List<Product> fresh = db.findTop100Products();
        cache.opsForValue().set("topProducts", fresh, Duration.ofHours(1));
        return fresh;
    }
}
```

**Scenario 3: Inconsistent cache keys lead to wrong user seeing wrong data**

```java
// BAD: cache key does not include tenant/user context
@Cacheable(value = "dashboard", key = "#reportType")
public DashboardData getDashboard(String reportType) {
    return db.getDashboard(currentUser(), reportType); // currentUser() not in cache key!
}
// User A requests "SALES" report → cached under key "SALES"
// User B requests "SALES" report → gets User A's data!

// GOOD: always scope key to user/tenant
@Cacheable(value = "dashboard", key = "#userId + ':' + #reportType")
public DashboardData getDashboard(Long userId, String reportType) {
    return db.getDashboard(userId, reportType);
}
```

**Scenario 4: Caching makes debugging impossible**

```
Customer: "I see wrong data on my profile page."
Dev: "I see correct data."
Customer: "Your fix didn't work."
Dev: "It did, but the cache still serves old data for 10 minutes."
```

Caches add a hidden time dimension to every bug. Log cache hits/misses in development, and always provide a cache-bust mechanism for support teams.

**Scenario 5: Memory pressure causes cascading evictions**

If the cache is too small relative to the working set, evictions happen constantly. Every eviction causes a DB read. Under load, the system thrashes: cache fills → evicts → refills → evicts. Net result: more load than no cache at all.

**When caching is clearly harmful:**
- Financial balances, inventory counts, or anything that must be real-time
- User-specific data unless the key includes the user ID
- Data that is written more often than it is read
- Small tables — a single DB index scan is often faster than a cache round-trip
- When the cache TTL is longer than the acceptable staleness window for that domain

Rate limiting protects your API from overuse — whether from abuse, a buggy client, or a legitimate traffic spike. A production implementation must be distributed (work across multiple app instances), precise, and fast. Redis is the standard backing store.

**Algorithm 1: Token Bucket (recommended — smooths bursts)**

Concept: A bucket holds N tokens. Each request consumes 1 token. Tokens refill at a fixed rate. If the bucket is empty, the request is rejected.

```
  Tokens: ████████░░   (8/10 available)
  Request arrives → consume 1 token → allowed
  Tokens: ███████░░░   (7/10 available)
  10 rapid requests → bucket empties → 429 Too Many Requests
  Tokens refill 2/sec → client can burst up to 10, then limited to 2/sec
```

**Redis implementation using Lua (atomic):**

```java
@Component
public class TokenBucketRateLimiter {

    @Autowired
    private StringRedisTemplate redis;

    // Lua script runs atomically — no race condition between check and decrement
    private static final String LUA_SCRIPT =
        "local key = KEYS[1] " +
        "local capacity = tonumber(ARGV[1]) " +
        "local refillRate = tonumber(ARGV[2]) " +
        "local now = tonumber(ARGV[3]) " +
        "local requested = tonumber(ARGV[4]) " +
        "local data = redis.call('HMGET', key, 'tokens', 'last_refill') " +
        "local tokens = tonumber(data[1]) or capacity " +
        "local lastRefill = tonumber(data[2]) or now " +
        "local elapsed = math.max(0, now - lastRefill) " +
        "tokens = math.min(capacity, tokens + elapsed * refillRate) " +
        "if tokens >= requested then " +
        "  tokens = tokens - requested " +
        "  redis.call('HMSET', key, 'tokens', tokens, 'last_refill', now) " +
        "  redis.call('EXPIRE', key, 3600) " +
        "  return 1 " +
        "else " +
        "  return 0 " +
        "end";

    public boolean isAllowed(String clientId, int capacity, double refillRatePerSec) {
        String key = "rate_limit:" + clientId;
        long nowMs = System.currentTimeMillis();
        double nowSeconds = nowMs / 1000.0;

        Long result = redis.execute(
            new DefaultRedisScript<>(LUA_SCRIPT, Long.class),
            List.of(key),
            String.valueOf(capacity),
            String.valueOf(refillRatePerSec),
            String.valueOf(nowSeconds),
            "1"
        );
        return Long.valueOf(1L).equals(result);
    }
}
```

**Spring filter that enforces the limit per API key:**

```java
@Component
public class RateLimitFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter {

    @Autowired
    private TokenBucketRateLimiter limiter;

    @Override
    protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest request,
                                    HttpServletResponse response,
                                    FilterChain chain)
            throws ServletException, IOException {

        String apiKey = request.getHeader("X-API-Key");
        if (apiKey == null) apiKey = request.getRemoteAddr(); // fallback to IP

        boolean allowed = limiter.isAllowed(
            apiKey,
            100,   // burst capacity: 100 requests
            10.0   // refill rate: 10 requests/sec
        );

        if (!allowed) {
            response.setStatus(HttpStatus.TOO_MANY_REQUESTS.value());
            response.setHeader("Retry-After", "1");
            response.getWriter().write("{\"error\": \"Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 1 second.\"}");
            return;
        }

        chain.doFilter(request, response);
    }
}
```

**Algorithm 2: Fixed Window Counter (simpler, boundary spike risk)**

```java
// Allow 1000 requests per minute per user
public boolean isAllowed(String userId) {
    String key = "rate:" + userId + ":" + (System.currentTimeMillis() / 60_000);
    Long count = redis.opsForValue().increment(key);
    if (count == 1) {
        redis.expire(key, Duration.ofMinutes(2)); // Cleanup
    }
    return count <= 1000;
}
// Risk: user sends 1000 at 00:59 and 1000 at 01:01 = 2000 in 2 seconds!
```

**Algorithm 3: Sliding Window Log (precise, memory-heavy)**

```java
// Store timestamp of every request in a sorted set
public boolean isAllowed(String userId, int maxRequests, Duration window) {
    String key = "ratelimit:" + userId;
    long now = System.currentTimeMillis();
    long windowStart = now - window.toMillis();

    // Remove old entries outside the window
    redis.opsForZSet().removeRangeByScore(key, 0, windowStart);

    // Count requests in the current window
    Long count = redis.opsForZSet().zCard(key);
    if (count != null && count >= maxRequests) return false;

    // Record this request
    redis.opsForZSet().add(key, String.valueOf(now), now);
    redis.expire(key, window.plusMinutes(1));
    return true;
}
```

**Production considerations:**
- Return `X-RateLimit-Remaining` and `X-RateLimit-Reset` headers so clients can self-throttle.
- Apply different limits per tier: free (10/sec), paid (100/sec), internal (unlimited).
- Rate limit by IP for unauthenticated endpoints, by API key for authenticated ones.
- Use Resilience4j's built-in `RateLimiter` if you don't want to manage Redis state manually.

"Works on my machine" is a cliché precisely because Java apps regularly behave differently across environments. The JVM, OS, and runtime context all vary in ways that are invisible until they cause production failures. Here are the most impactful differences:

**1. JVM heap and GC configuration**

```bash
# Local (developer laptop): default JVM flags
java -jar app.jar
# JVM auto-configures: heap = 25% of RAM, GC = G1GC
# On a 16GB MacBook: -Xmx4g implicitly

# Production (containerized): often under-configured
java -jar app.jar
# Container has 512MB RAM → JVM takes 128MB max heap
# With 10k concurrent users, frequent full GC pauses → timeout storms

# Fix: always set JVM flags explicitly in prod
java -Xms512m -Xmx512m \
     -XX:+UseG1GC \
     -XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=200 \
     -jar app.jar

# Diagnose: run this and compare outputs between environments
java -XX:+PrintFlagsFinal -version | grep -E "HeapSize|GCPolicy"
```

**2. Container memory limits — JVM doesn't see them by default (pre-Java 10)**

```bash
# Docker limits container to 512MB
# Old JVM (Java 8 < 8u191): reads HOST memory (e.g., 64GB)
# JVM sets heap to 25% of 64GB = 16GB → OOMKilled by container runtime!

# Fix: use Java 11+ (container-aware) or set explicit flags
java -XX:+UseContainerSupport   # Default in Java 11+
     -XX:MaxRAMPercentage=75.0  # Use 75% of container RAM
     -jar app.jar
```

**3. Thread count and I/O scheduling**

```java
// Default ForkJoinPool uses available processors
// Local: 8-core MacBook → 8 threads
// Prod: 2-vCPU container → 2 threads

ForkJoinPool.commonPool().getParallelism(); // Returns 7 locally, 1 in prod!

// This breaks parallel stream assumptions:
List<Product> products = db.findAll();
products.parallelStream()  // 8 threads locally = fast, 2 threads in prod = slow
    .map(this::enrich)
    .collect(toList());

// Fix: use explicit thread pools with documented sizing
ExecutorService pool = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(
    Math.max(4, Runtime.getRuntime().availableProcessors() * 2)
);
```

**4. File paths, line endings, and encoding**

```java
// BAD: Hardcoded local path
File config = new File("/Users/dev/app/config.yml"); // Fails everywhere else

// BAD: Default charset (depends on OS locale)
String content = new String(bytes); // UTF-8 on Mac, Windows-1252 on Windows Server!

// GOOD:
String content = new String(bytes, StandardCharsets.UTF_8); // Explicit everywhere

// BAD: Windows line endings in shell scripts deployed to Linux
// Script has \r\n → Linux bash cannot parse → "file not found" error on startup

// Fix: configure .gitattributes
# .gitattributes
*.sh text eol=lf
*.yml text eol=lf
```

**5. Environment variables and secrets**

```java
// Local: uses application-local.yml with real dev credentials
// Prod: uses environment variables injected by Kubernetes

@Value("${db.password}")
private String dbPassword;

// If DB_PASSWORD env var is missing in prod → startup fails with:
// "Could not resolve placeholder 'db.password'"

// Defensive: always provide defaults or fail with a clear message
@Value("${db.password:#{null}}")
private String dbPassword;

@PostConstruct
public void validate() {
    if (dbPassword == null)
        throw new IllegalStateException(
            "DB_PASSWORD environment variable is required in production");
}
```

**6. JIT compilation behaviour**

```
Local load test: 10 users → JVM barely JIT-compiles hot paths
Prod traffic: 10,000 users → JVM profile-guided optimizations kick in fully

Result: a method that is naively implemented but never hot locally
becomes a bottleneck when JIT can no longer inline it due to mega-morphic
call sites (too many different concrete types at the same call site).

Diagnose: -XX:+PrintCompilation to see what JIT does under real load
```

**7. Network latency and timeout assumptions**

```java
// Local: DB is on localhost → 0.1ms latency
// Prod: DB is in a different AZ → 1–5ms latency
// 1000 sequential DB calls: local = 100ms, prod = 1–5 seconds!

// Fix: batch queries, use connection pools, profile with realistic latency
// Simulate prod latency locally with tc netem:
// sudo tc qdisc add dev lo root netem delay 5ms
```

**Diagnosis toolkit:**

```bash
# Compare JVM effective flags between environments
java -XX:+PrintFlagsFinal -version 2>&1 | sort > local-flags.txt
# (run same in prod, diff the files)

# Heap histogram (what objects are filling memory?)
jcmd <pid> VM.native_memory
jmap -histo:live <pid> | head -30

# Thread dump (is anything stuck?)
jstack <pid> > threaddump.txt
grep -c 'BLOCKED' threaddump.txt  # Should be 0

# GC logs — always enable in prod
-Xlog:gc*:file=/var/log/app-gc.log:time,uptime:filecount=5,filesize=20m
```

The root cause of most prod-vs-local differences is unexamined assumptions about resources (RAM, CPU, disk, network). Make every assumption explicit in configuration.

Understanding JVM object allocation is critical for writing high-throughput Java. Under heavy load, the allocation path changes dynamically, and naive object creation patterns can bring a service to its knees through GC pressure.

**The generational heap layout (G1GC, default in Java 9+):**

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                        JVM HEAP                             │
│                                                             │
│  ┌──────────────────────────────┐  ┌──────────────────────┐ │
│  │        Young Generation      │  │   Old Generation     │ │
│  │  ┌────────┐  ┌────┐ ┌────┐  │  │  (Tenured Space)     │ │
│  │  │  Eden  │  │ S0 │ │ S1 │  │  │  Long-lived objects  │ │
│  │  │(fast   │  │(Sur│ │(Sur│  │  │  Large allocations   │ │
│  │  │ alloc) │  │ v0)│ │ v1)│  │  │                      │ │
│  │  └────────┘  └────┘ └────┘  │  └──────────────────────┘ │
│  └──────────────────────────────┘                           │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Step 1: Thread-Local Allocation Buffer (TLAB) — the fast path**

Every thread gets its own private chunk of Eden (a TLAB). Allocation is just a pointer bump — no locking, no synchronization:

```java
// This allocation is nearly free (nanoseconds)
String s = new String("hello"); // Pointer bump in TLAB

// JVM internal (conceptual):
// if (tlab.top + objectSize <= tlab.end) {
//     Object obj = tlab.top;
//     tlab.top += objectSize;
//     return obj;   // No lock needed!
// } else {
//     slowAllocationPath(); // TLAB full, get a new one
// }
```

Under heavy load: if threads allocate faster than GC can collect, TLABs refill constantly, eventually exhausting Eden.

**Step 2: Minor GC (Young GC) — triggered when Eden is full**

```
Eden fills up
   │
   ▼
Minor GC triggered (stop-the-world, but short — typically 5–50ms)
   │
   ├─ Live objects in Eden → copied to Survivor space (S0 or S1)
   ├─ Objects that survived N GC cycles (age threshold) → promoted to Old
   └─ Dead objects → memory reclaimed, Eden cleared
```

```java
// Objects that escape methods get promoted quickly
@Service
public class ReportService {

    // BAD: Creates large list on every call, survives GC cycles
    public List<ReportRow> generateReport() {
        List<ReportRow> rows = new ArrayList<>(); // Allocated in Eden
        for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++) {
            rows.add(new ReportRow(db.get(i))); // Lives across GC cycles
        }
        return rows; // Promoted to Old generation
    }
    // With 100 concurrent report requests:
    // Old generation fills rapidly → Full GC (long stop-the-world!)
}
```

**Step 3: Large object allocation (Humongous Objects in G1GC)**

```java
// Objects larger than ~50% of a G1 region (default region = 1–32MB)
// are allocated directly in Old generation, skipping Eden entirely

byte[] largeBuffer = new byte[50 * 1024 * 1024]; // 50MB → goes straight to Old!

// This is expensive because:
// 1. Allocation in Old gen requires a lock (no TLAB)
// 2. Old gen GC (Full GC) is much slower than Young GC
// 3. Fragmentation can prevent future large allocations

// Check region size:
// -XX:G1HeapRegionSize=16m  (tune based on workload)
```

**Step 4: GC pressure and allocation failure under load**

```
Scenario: 10,000 req/sec, each allocating 10KB of short-lived objects

Allocation rate = 100 MB/sec
Eden size = 500 MB
Eden fills in 5 seconds → Minor GC every 5 seconds

If each Minor GC takes 50ms:
50ms pause every 5s = 1% pause overhead (acceptable)

Now: allocation rate spikes to 1000 MB/sec (traffic surge)
Eden fills in 0.5 seconds → Minor GC every 500ms
50ms pause every 500ms = 10% pause overhead → latency p99 spikes!
```

**Diagnosing allocation pressure:**

```bash
# Real-time GC events
-Xlog:gc*:file=/tmp/gc.log:time,uptime

# Allocation rate (objects/sec)
jcmd <pid> VM.native_memory

# What is being allocated? (heap histogram)
jmap -histo:live <pid> | head -20
# Output:
#  num     instances         bytes  class name
#    1:      5000000     120000000  [B  (byte arrays)
#    2:      2000000      48000000  java.lang.String
#    3:      1000000      24000000  com.app.ReportRow
```

**Reducing allocation pressure in production:**

```java
// 1. Object pooling for expensive objects
public class ConnectionPool {
    private final BlockingQueue<Connection> pool;

    public Connection borrow() throws InterruptedException {
        return pool.poll(100, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS); // Reuse, don't allocate
    }

    public void release(Connection conn) {
        pool.offer(conn); // Return to pool
    }
}

// 2. Avoid boxing in hot paths
// BAD: autoboxing creates Integer objects in Eden
Map<Integer, Integer> counts = new HashMap<>();
for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++) {
    counts.merge(i % 100, 1, Integer::sum); // Boxes int to Integer every iteration
}

// GOOD: use primitive-specialised collections (Eclipse Collections, Trove)
MutableIntIntMap counts = IntIntMaps.mutable.empty();
for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++) {
    counts.addToValue(i % 100, 1); // No boxing
}

// 3. Escape analysis — JVM may allocate on stack instead of heap
public void process() {
    Point p = new Point(1, 2); // JVM may eliminate heap allocation
    System.out.println(p.x + p.y); // p doesn't escape this method
    // -XX:+DoEscapeAnalysis (on by default) detects this
}
```

**JVM GC algorithm choice matters under load:**

```
G1GC (default, Java 9+):  Predictable pause times, good for 4GB+ heaps
ZGC (Java 15+):            Sub-millisecond pauses, ideal for latency-sensitive APIs
Shenandoah (Java 12+):    Similar to ZGC, concurrent compaction

For a high-traffic API where p99 latency matters:
java -XX:+UseZGC -Xmx4g -jar app.jar
# ZGC pauses < 1ms even on 100GB heaps
```
